text.b: Northeast Corner of East Boronda Road and San Juan Grade
City of Salinas, Monterey County, California

page.text: As requested, EEI has completed a preliminary geotechnical evaluation for the proposed Lowes Home
Improvement Warehouse, Inc. (Lowes HIW, Inc.) site in Salinas, California. The scope of work
associated with this preliminary geotechnical evaluation is based upon discussions with Lowes staff, our
review of a preliminary site plan, and our limited field exploration of the subject property. EEI conducted
this preliminary geotechnical evaluation to assess the overall feasibility of the project and to provide
preliminary recommendations for planning purposes. In order to satisfy Lowes Development Criteria,
and to provide appropriate recommendations for design and construction of the proposed improvements at
the site, an additional design-level geotechnical evaluation will be warranted.
This evaluation is based upon the review of a preliminary site plan of the Salinas Retail Project (of which
Lowes is a part) by AMS Associates, Inc. (dated January 13, 2010) provided by the Client, as well as
EEIs research of readily available regional geologic reports and maps, our recent limited field
exploration (April 23 and 24, 2010) and our experience in the area. A summary of preliminary findings,
conclusions and recommendations are provided herein.
Based upon our review of the aforementioned site plan by AMS Associates, Inc., existing elevations
and/or proposed finish grade elevations are not provided; therefore, the amount of cut and fill grading is
unknown. For the purpose of this limited evaluation, however, the existing plans are considered to be
appropriate. Based upon this limited geotechnical evaluation, EEI will propose additional field studies
pertaining to site development, which should be based upon more detailed civil engineering plans.

text.b: Lowes of Salinas, Monterey County, California

page.text: The subject site is situated in northern Monterey County roughly 8-miles east of the Pacific Ocean and
approximately -mile east of Highway 101 in the northern portion of the City of Salinas, California. The
property, located at the northeast corner of East Boronda Road and San Juan Grade Road, is presently
being cultivated for agricultural purposes. Current access to the site is via East Boronda Road and San
Juan Grade Road, which bound the property to the southwest and northwest, respectively. The site is
bounded on the north and east by agricultural land, and to the south and west predominantly by residential
and a shopping center (Harden Plaza). A school is located in the vicinity to the east. Based on our
conversations with the farm manger, we understand that a well was present along the western margin of
the property as recently as the 1980s, and a buried water line is still present beneath the property,
extending southeast from the former well location.
Our review of a preliminary site plan prepared by AMS Associates, Inc. (dated January 13, 2010)
indicates that the Lowes Home Improvement Warehouse (HIW) store (i.e., Parcel 1) is planned for the
northern portion of the Salinas Retail Project and consists of 11.65 acres within the 17-acre project. The
Lowes structure, which is to be comprised of 120,944 square feet of retail space, will have an attached
31,384 square-foot garden center on the western side of the building. The main parking area is planned
south of the building with the loading dock in the northwesterly corner of the structure. A storm water
detention area is planned for the northwestern section of the property. Bioswales are also planned
within the parking lot islands. We understand that development of the remainder of the retail project will
include four (4) retail out-parcels located on the southern (i.e., Parcels 2 and 3) and western (i.e., Parcel 4)
perimeter of the project. The aforementioned site plan notes that storm drain retention areas are proposed
for the development off the easterly side of the future retail center. We anticipate that all proposed retail
development will be of slab-on-grade construction. While no grading plans have been provided for our
review, it is anticipated that grading at the site will likely include cut and fill of less than ten feet across
the site (exclusive of any remedial grading).
The subject property is located on the United States Geological Survey (USGS) Salinas, California 7.5
Minute Quadrangle map. This topographic/geographic map indicates that elevations on the subject
property range from approximately 100 feet above mean sea level (amsl) to 95 feet amsl. The ground
surface at the site gently slopes toward the southwest. Based on topography, surface drainage generally
appears to flow in a southwesterly direction, ultimately into Markeley Swamp (City of Salinas, 2004).
Soils classification onsite was determined using the United Stated Department of Agriculture Natural
Resources Conservation Service website (Web Soil Survey). The subject property falls within the soil
survey for Monterey County, California. The survey area data is based upon Version 9, dated April 14,
2009, with aerial images dated June 13, 2005. The dominant soil map unit is the Chualar loam (0 to 2

page.text: This soil type is not reported by the soil survey to contain calcium carbonate or gypsum. The soil is listed
with a pH in the range of 6.1 to 7.8, and contains 45 to 60 percent sand and 10 to 25 percent clay to a
depth on the order of 5 feet below the ground surface (bgs). The Plastic Index, which indicates the
plasticity of the soil, is listed to range from non plastic to 15 within the same depth. The United Soil
Classification System (USCS) for the Chualar loam is noted by the soil survey report to be typically
comprised of silty sand (SM) and clayey sand (SC). The American Association of State Highway and
Transportation Officials (AASHTO) classification is listed as A-1 to A-6. The erosion factor for whole
soil (Kw), which indicates the susceptibility of a soil to sheet or rill by water, is listed in the soil survey
report as ranging from 0.24 to 0.32. The Kf factor, or the erodibilty of the fine-earth fraction of soil, is
listed at 0.32 to 0.43. Values of K range from 0.02 to 0.69. All factors being equal, the higher the K
value, the more susceptible the soil is to sheet or rill erosion by water. The saturated hydraulic
conductivity (Ksat) is rated at 10.95 micrometers per second (m/s) by the soil survey report. The wind
erodibility index, a numerical value indicating the susceptibility of a soil to wind erosion, for the Chualar
loam is reported as 56 (tons per acre per year). The sewage lagoon absorption rating is listed in the soil
survey with limitations, with permeability listed as ranging from 0.6- to 2-inches per hour.
The City of Salinas Stormwater Master Plan (2004) and the development standards (2008) list the Chualar
loams within the B-low hydrologic soil group, or soils having moderate infiltration rates when thoroughly
The property lies within the Coastal Ranges geomorphic province of California (CGS, 2002), a northwest
southeast orientated system of mountains and valleys along the central and northern California coast.
The Coast Ranges are comprised predominantly of Mesozoic and Cenozoic sedimentary units. West of
the San Andreas Fault zone, which is located near the eastern boundary of the province, is the Salinian
Regional mapping (Wagner, Greene and Pridmore, 2002) indicates the subject property is underlain by
Pleistocene-age alluvial fan deposits. Previously, the Salinas area east of Highway 101 was mapped as
The project area lies within the California Department of Water Resources (DWR) Salinas Valley Basin
of the Central Coast Hydrologic Region. In this region, 1995 data indicates groundwater provides
approximately 80 percent of agricultural and suburban use. Due to marine sedimentary units in this
region, groundwater is typically characterized by elevated levels of calcium sulfate and calcium sodium
bicarbonate sulfate. Aquifers affected by seawater intrusion have elevated concentrations of calcium
chloride and sodium chloride exceeding 500 milligrams per liter (DWR, 2003).
According to the California Regional Water Quality Control Board, Central Coast Region (Region 3)
Basin Plan (1994), the subject site is located within the Salinas Valley Groundwater Basin of the Central
Coastal Hydrologic Study area. Groundwater in this sub area has been designated as beneficial for
municipal and domestic supply, agricultural, and industrial process supply. Surface water in the
immediate vicinity of the subject property is located within the Chualar Hydrologic Area of the Salinas
Hydrologic Unit; however, there appears to be no surface water bodies within or in the immediate vicinity

page.text: EEI reviewed the Citys stormwater master plan (City of Salinas, 2004), which shows the subject property
in future development areas. The maps suggest that the subject property (north of Boronda Road) is
within the Markeley Swamp watershed. Markeley Swamp is noted to be a tributary to the Reclamation
Ditch system, flowing northwesterly through south-central portion of the City of Salinas. The report notes
that existing drainage problems occur at the City boundary where runoff from farmlands impacts the
cities stormdrain system(s). The area north of the City along Boronda Road is referenced in the report as
EEIs field observations detected no groundwater wells within the subject property boundaries; however,
research indicates that there is a buried water well near the edge of San Juan Grade Road. According to
statements made by the current farm manger, we understand that this well was present along the western
margin of the property as recently as the 1980s. It is our understanding that a buried concrete irrigation
line (12-inches in diameter) trends northeast from the west edge of the site through the proposed Lowes
building envelope. Indications are that the line is buried within 4 feet of the existing ground surface.
There are no public records that this well has been properly abandoned. Our site observations indicate that
per the guidelines of the local jurisdiction other surface irrigation lines are visible onsite which convey
irrigation water to the subject property from a private well situated offsite to the northeast. As noted
during our recent field exploration, groundwater was not encountered to a maximum explored depth of
51-feet below the ground surface (bgs). Our discussions with the current property farmer indicate that
groundwater is at depths on the order of 160 to 220 feet bgs
EEI reviewed an electronic copy of the City of Salinas General Plan (dated September 2002) to determine
whether the subject property is located within an area designated as a Flood Hazard Zone. According to
the information reviewed, the subject property is not situated within an area identified as a 100-year flood
zone. The General Plan does note, however, that potential flood risks exist within Salinas Valley due to
development within 100-year floodplains, levee failure, local drainage problems and dam failure. The
Salinas River Valley and the Carmel River Valley, both located southwest of the subject property, are
considered to have the greatest risk of dam failure in Monterey County.
Mass wasting is related to processes by which surficial soils and/or bedrock materials move down
gradient as a result of gravity. Due to the relatively level ground surface at the subject site, surface
expressions of landsliding, slumps, creep, or other surficial failures were not observed within the subject
property during our field reconnaissance. Graded slopes (if proposed), should be evaluated for their
stability once finalized grading plans become available.
There are a number of faults in central California that are considered active and would likely generate
ground shaking should they be the source of an earthquake. Active faults in the immediate site area
include (but are not limited to) the San Andreas Fault zone (to the north-northeast), the Calaveras Fault
zone (to the northeast), the Palo Colorado-San Gregorio Fault zone (offshore to the northwest), and the
Monterey Bay Fault zone (offshore to the northwest).

Liquefaction is a phenomenon in which the strength and stiffness of a soil is reduced by earthquake
shaking or other rapid loading. Liquefaction and related phenomena have been responsible for substantial
structural damage in historical earthquakes, and are a design concern under certain conditions.
Liquefaction occurs in saturated soils, that is, soils in which the space between individual particles is
completely filled with water. This pore water exerts a pressure on the soil particles that influences how
tightly the particles themselves are pressed together.

text.b: Lowes of Salinas, Monterey County, California

page.text: Based upon our preliminary evaluation and limited field exploration, the subject site does not appear to be
susceptible to earthquake induced liquefaction or significant amounts of seismic induced ground
settlement, based on the nature of the encountered subsurface materials and the observed lack of
groundwater to the maximum explored depth of 51 fee bgs.
The purpose of our preliminary subsurface field evaluation was to characterize the overall geologic and
geotechnical conditions to assist Lowes HIW in evaluating the feasibility of the proposed construction at
the site. Five (5) borings were advanced on the Lowes property (Parcel 1) and six (6) borings were
drilled on the overall property (Parcels 2, 3 and 4), at the general locations as noted on the boring
Field exploration was conducted by EEI on April 23 and 24, 2010. Due to the preliminary nature of the
requested geotechnical study, and as approved by Lowes project management, the field study presented
herein was not in general accordance with Lowes Site Development Specifications. The borings were
evaluated for near-surface geologic conditions for the construction of the Lowes building. Borings were
logged under the supervision of an EEI registered professional engineer.
Since the subject property is presently cultivated for agricultural purposes, the ground surface within the
site was soft, and would not accommodate a conventional truck-mounted drill rig. As a result, borings
were advance using a limited access drill rig.
Small diameter (i.e., 8-inches) hollow stem auger borings were advanced within the site to obtain the
subsurface data. Borings advanced within the proposed Lowes HIW building envelope extended to
depths between 31 and 51 feet bgs. Within the parking lot, borings were drilled to a depth of 16
Our field studies included soil sample collection and laboratory testing to provide data for preliminary
geotechnical evaluation and the development of preliminary soils engineering recommendations regarding
the proposed site development, including foundation design recommendations and pavement design
Blow count (N) values were determined utilizing a 140 pound automatic hammer, falling 30-inches onto a
Standard Penetration Test (SPT) split-spoon sampler and a Modified California split-tube sampler. The
number of blows (N value) required to advance the 18-inch long SPT and 12-inch long Modified

5-foot intervals (recorded on the boring logs), and are presented in Appendix A-Soil Classification Chart
and Boring Logs. Relatively undisturbed samples were collected in a 2.42-inch (inside diameter)
California Modified split-tube sampler for visual examination and laboratory testing. Representative bulk
samples were collected for appropriate laboratory testing. The soils were classified in accordance with

text.b: Lowes of Salinas, Monterey County, California

page.text: Pleistocene-aged (i.e., Recent) alluvial fan deposits were encountered in our exploratory borings to the
maximum explored depth of approximately 51 feet bgs. Where encountered, these deposits were
observed to be comprised commonly of brown and orange-brown silty sands to a depth of approximately
15 feet bgs, where sandy and silty clays interbedded with silty sands were found. The sandy portions of
these materials were noted to be typically slightly moist to very moist and loose to medium dense at the
time of our subsurface exploration. The clayey portions were observed to be moist and medium stiff to
stiff at the time of our subsurface exploration. As is typical with active farmlands, elevated
concentrations of organic materials were observed within the upper topsoil layer, where it was observed
to be on the order of 1(+/-)-foot in thickness; however, soil disturbance due to cultivation was observed to
be on the order of 2-foot bgs. A more detailed description of the encountered soils is provided on the
boring logs included as Appendix A.
Groundwater was not encountered in any of our exploratory borings that were drilled to a maximum depth
of 51 feet below the existing ground surface. It should be noted, however, that variations in
groundwater may result from fluctuations in the ground surface topography, subsurface stratification,
rainfall, irrigation, and other factors that may not have been evident at the time of our exploration.
Representative samples were selected for laboratory testing to confirm their field classifications. Field
descriptions and classifications were visually classified according to the American Society for Testing
and Materials (ASTM) D-2488, which classifies soils under the Unified Soil Classification System
(USCS). Representative soil samples were tested in the lab for grain size distribution, liquid limits, and
plastic limits to determine actual classifications by ASTM D-2487-Standard Practice for Classification of
Soils for Engineering Purposes in accordance with the USCS. Final classifications of soils can be found
on the boring logs in Appendix A and the laboratory test data in Appendix B.
To check classifications of soils and to help evaluate liquefaction potential at the site, grain size
distribution of representative soil samples was determined. In order to find the percentages of different
sized particles in a particular soil stratum, soils were tested in general accordance to ASTM D-422-
Standard Test Method for Particle-Size Analysis of Soils. Grain size distribution curves and gradation
results are presented in Appendix B.

page.text: The liquid limit, plastic limit, and plasticity index (PI) of soils were determined to aid in the classification
of soils (i.e., distinguishing clay from silt) and to evaluate the potential for expansion and seismically-
induced liquefaction. The tests were performed in general accordance to ASTM D-4318. The results are

text.b: Lowes of Salinas, Monterey County, California

page.text: The in-situ moisture content and dry density of soils were determined for soil samples obtained from the
borings. Moisture contents and dry densities of soils help to determine engineering design parameters for
foundations, retaining walls, and other engineered structures. Moisture content on soil samples was
conducted in general accordance with ASTM D-2216, and was recorded as a percentage. In-place
moisture content and dry density information for soil samples retrieved from the field can be found on the
boring logs located in Appendix A.

text.b: Maximum Dry Density and Optimum Moisture Content

page.text: The maximum dry density and optimum moisture content was determined from representative bulk soil
samples obtained within the upper five feet of existing grade. Our testing was performed in general
accordance with ASTM D-1557, Method B. Results of our testing are presented in Appendix B.
Direct shear testing was conducted on representative soil samples that were remolded to 92 percent of
their maximum dry density (based on ASTM D-1557) to measure their shear strength characteristics for
engineering purposes. The samples were then inundated for at least 18 hours. The samples were placed
in a shear box and a normal load was applied (10, 20, and 40 kilogram weights were used). The sample
was then sheared at a controlled strain rate in a direct shear apparatus that measures horizontal
displacement and shear resistance. Shear testing was run in general accordance to ASTM D-3080. The
results of our testing are presented in Appendix B.
Two (2) soil samples obtained from within the upper five feet of existing grade within the 17-acre site as
a whole were tested for their expansion potential. Clayey soils can be expansive with the introduction of
water and can cause heaving. Our expansion index (i.e., EI) testing was conducted in general accordance
to ASTM D-4829. The result of our expansion index testing is presented in Appendix B.
Expansion index testing should be completed at the conclusion of rough grading, and should consist of
the evaluation of soils within four feet of finish grade. Additional testing, therefore, is recommended
after completion of rough building pad grade.
A representative bulk sample from the upper five feet of earth materials encountered within the proposed
parking area was collected for R-Value testing. Pavement design is based upon these test results. The
samples were sent to the GeoSoils, Inc. soils laboratory in Carlsbad, California. Test procedures were
conducted in general accordance with the Department of Transportation, State of California, and
Materials & Research Test Method No. 301. The R-Value test results are presented in Appendix B.
Verification testing is recommended at the conclusion of grading on samples collected at (or near) finish

Consolidation properties of soils were determined to evaluate soil potential for compression and long-
term settlement. The consolidation test method includes measuring the amount and rate of consolidation
of soil when subject to loading. The test was run with relatively undisturbed soil samples in 1-inch thick
brass rings, collected from the Modified California sampler. The samples were placed in a
consolidometer with porous stones at the top and bottom of the sample and placed in a loading frame.
Weights were added and measurements of height were recorded from a dial indicator as the sample was
compressed. Measurements of height were also recorded during the rebound period of removal of the
weights. Consolidation testing was performed in general accordance to ASTM D-2435. Results of our
consolidation testing are presented in Appendix B.
Based on our limited field study and cursory research of regional and local geologic reports and maps, the
subject property in Salinas, California appears feasible for the proposed commercial development from a
geotechnical engineering and geologic viewpoint, provided the preliminary recommendations contained
in the following sections of this report are properly incorporated into design of the site improvements.
Based upon the scope of this limited geotechnical evaluation, additional field studies and evaluation
pertaining to site development are recommended, which would be based upon more detailed project plans.
As a result, EEI is providing the following preliminary conclusions:
The 11.65-acre Lowes of Salinas property is a part of a 17-acre retail project planned at the
northeastern corner of San Juan Grade Road and East Boronda Road. The property is
currently being actively farmed with recently harvested and/or cultivated sections. Due to
seasonal precipitation, surface water was observed onsite during our limited field study.
Agricultural development of the site has created an organic topsoil layer on the order of
1(+/-)-foot in thickness. Cultivation appears to have disturbed the upper 2 feet of soils onsite.
Buried concrete irrigation lines exist within the site.

text.b: Lowes of Salinas, Monterey County, California

page.text: The site is relatively level, with the ground sloping gently to the southwest. Without the
benefit of existing or proposed elevations, it is impractical to estimate the amount of grading
that will be needed to create a building pad for a 120,944 square-foot building, an attached
31,384 square-foot garden center, and associated parking lot. EEI anticipates, however, that
typical cut and fill grading operations will be used to develop the property. Standard heavy
duty grading equipment (in proper working order) may be utilized to conduct earthwork
onsite without significant difficulty associated with groundwater and/or over-sized rock
At this time, there appears to be no unmitigatible geologic hazards that would place unusual
constraints on the project; however, additional field exploration is recommended to check the
uniformity of subsurface conditions within the subject property. Additional borings within
the Lowes parcel are also recommended to comply with Lowes HIW, Inc. specifications
The subject property is underlain by recent alluvial fan deposits with the upper portions
consisting of fine- to coarse-grained sands with minor silt. Below a depth of approximately
15 feet bgs, clayey alluvial soils are commonly interbedded with sands and silts.
Groundwater was not encountered in any of our exploratory borings that were drilled to a
maximum depth of 51 bgs within the property. Additionally, the cohesionless nature of
sandy alluvial soils may represent trench safety issues that will require consideration.
According to the current farm manger, a water well was present along the western margin of
the property as recently as the 1980s, and a buried water line is still present beneath the
property, extending northeasterly from the former well location through the proposed Lowes
building envelope. Another line also is thought to trend along the western edge of the site,
near San Juan Grade Road. This well should be properly abandoned following State of
California Department of Water Resources standards (1991). Well abandonment should be
completed by a licensed water well drilling contractor.
The site is located in a seismically active area and strong ground shaking from earthquakes
should be anticipated and incorporated into project design.
Buried concrete irrigation lines exist within the site that will require removal and offsite
disposal during earthwork. Care should be taken during initial removals to verify that the
concrete pipes do not contain asbestos. The pipes should not be broken or crushed before
evaluation by an experienced environmental professional.

to reduce the potential for excessive post-construction settlement, remedial earthwork appears
to be warranted to provide a sufficient layer of engineered fill beneath the

with a minimum resistivity of between 1,200 and 1,920 ohm-cm. Buried ferrous metal lines
should be provided with appropriate protection from direct soil contact in accordance with the
recommendations of a qualified corrosion consultant.
Laboratory test results indicated soluble sulfate concentrations of between 47 and 80
milligrams per kilogram (mg/kg) and chloride concentrations of between 31 and 55 mg/kg.
As a result, onsite soils appear to have a negligible corrosion potential to concrete. Based on
this information, Type II cement can be used in concrete that will be in contact with the
Results of laboratory testing indicated nitrate concentrations between 188 and 387 mg/kg,

considered to pose a threat as such, we recommend that a qualified corrosion engineer be

Based on our preliminary geotechnical evaluation, it is EEIs opinion that geotechnical conditions are
favorable for the use of conventional shallow foundations for the support of the proposed retail
structure(s). To provide relatively uniform foundation support underlying the future building envelope
and to reduce the potential for excessive post-construction settlement, remedial earthwork appears to be
warranted to provide a sufficient layer of engineered fill beneath the footings/foundations.
Grading and site development plans should conform to the guidelines presented in the 2007 California

Department of Health guidelines. Subsurface areas disturbed by irrigation lines and utility demolition

Areas to receive fill should be properly benched in accordance with current industry standards of practice
and guidelines specified in the CBC, 2007.
If unanticipated, subsurface improvements (utility lines, septic systems, wells, utilities, etc.) are

Based upon the limited subsurface data collected from the five (5) borings drilled within the Lowes
parcel, removals are recommended to reprocess existing earth materials disturbed by farming and
cultivation. Additionally, remedial earthwork is anticipated to reprocess the upper portions of soft and
compressible alluvial soils within the building envelope and parking area. As discussed previously,

removal and remedial earthwork depths are not practical for this limited geotechnical evaluation. Based

remedial earthwork depth of 5 feet of existing onsite soils within the building envelope. Independent of
remedial earthwork, EEI recommends that building foundations, including loading dock walls, should be
underlain by at least 2 to 3 feet of compacted fill.

elevation(s) is made available. Buried irrigation lines should be completely removed within the subject
Following remedial earthwork, the bottom of the resulting excavations should be proof-rolled with a
tandem-axle dump truck, a water truck or similar rubber tired vehicle. Soils which are observed to rut or
deflect excessively under the moving load should be undercut and replaced with properly compacted fill.
The proof-rolling and undercutting activities should be observed by a representative of EEI and should be
performed during dry weather. It should be understood that based on our field representatives
observations, localized deeper removals may be recommended. Once removals are completed and
observed by EEI, the exposed bottom should be reprocessed/scarified to a depth of at least 6-inches,
moisture conditioned to at least optimum moisture content and compacted to a minimum of 92 percent (or
95 percent within 1 feet of finish grade) of the maximum dry density (based on ASTM D-1557) prior to
placement of additional fill soils (Lowes, 2009). Where not affected by existing surface improvements
boundaries, removals should be completed below a 1:1 projection down and away from the edge of any
settlement sensitive structure and/or limits of proposed fill.
Following removal of the disturbed soils within pavement areas (i.e., parking lot), the bottom of the
resulting excavation(s) should be observed by a representative of EEI to check that the unsuitable
materials have been sufficiently removed. It should be understood that based on our field representatives
observations, localized deeper removals may be recommended. Once removals are completed and
observed by EEI, the exposed bottom should be reprocessed/scarified to a depth of at least 6-inches,
moisture conditioned to at least optimum moisture content and compacted to a minimum of 92 percent (or
95 percent within 1 feet of finish grade) of the maximum dry density (based on ASTM D-1557) prior to
Decreasing the recommended depth of remedial earthwork within the building envelope may increase the
amount of total and/or differential settlement to levels that exceed Lowes Development Criteria
tolerances; therefore, EEI should further evaluate settlement and the preliminary removal depths once
additional field borings are completed and grading plans are available.
Lowes guidelines, Section 02300 - Earthwork dictate that clean fill should consist of well graded
granular soils which are non-expansive and non-collapsible, and should have less than 20 percent by
weight passing the No. 200 sieve (Lowes, 2009). EEIs laboratory evaluation and field observations
indicates that native soils are relatively easy to excavate, slightly moist to moist near the ground surface,
have a very low expansion potential and are non-collapsible below a depth of 5 to 5 feet below the
existing ground surface. It is EEIs opinion that onsite non-organic native soils may be reused as fill
soils. Lowes criteria allows for the use of onsite soils as fill materials provided they are moisture
conditioned (as needed) and blended with native finer-grained soils to create a blanket of compacted fill
with between 5 percent fines (soils passing the No. 200 sieve), and 20 percent fines (per Lowes
guidelines). Based on our preliminary geotechnical evaluation, EEI recommends footings/foundations
should be underlain by at least 2 feet of compacted fill.

that these soils be compacted with moisture content of at least optimum (based on ASTM D-1557). Fill

If import soils are needed, the earthwork contractor should ensure that all proposed fill materials are

Shrinkage/bulking for the site has been estimated based upon our laboratory testing, visual site
observations during our subsurface exploration, and experience with similar soils, based on the results of
our preliminary evaluation. Tentatively, EEI estimates approximately 10 to 15 percent shrinkage of
native soils during earthwork onsite. These factors may vary with the method employed by the
contractor. Subsidence is estimated to be on the order of 0.15 feet. Losses from site clearing and removal
of disturbed and cultivated soils may affect earthwork quantity calculation and should be considered.
While not anticipated at the site, layers containing oversize cobble and boulder size materials within the
native alluvial soils can also be expected to affect earthwork quantities.
The following conclusions and recommendations contained in this report are considered preliminary in
nature, and shall not be considered final. The preliminary foundation recommendations provided herein
may be used solely for planning purposes. Foundation recommendations are subject to further evaluation
and revision based upon EEIs findings during the design-level geotechnical evaluation.

page.text: The proposed structure can be supported on conventional continuous and isolated spread footings that are
bearing upon at least 24-inches of engineered fill compacted to at least 92 percent relative compaction
(ASTM D-1557). In preparation for foundation construction, the earthwork contractor should ensure that
the site has been prepared as recommended, and that field density tests have been performed to document
the relative compaction of all structural fill.
For preliminary purposes, footings can be designed to impose dead plus long term live load bearing
pressures of 3,000 pounds per square foot (psf). The allowable soil bearing value is based on a footing
having a minimum width of 12-inches and a minimum depth of 18-inches embedment below lowest
adjacent finish grade. The allowable soil bearing pressure can be increased by 300 psf for each additional
foot of embedment or width to a maximum value of 4,000 psf. The allowable soil bearing value can also
be increased by one-third when considering load combinations that include transient loading, including
Horizontal loads acting on foundations and stem walls cast in open excavations against properly placed
and compacted fill will be resisted by friction acting along the base of the footing and by passive earth
pressures against the side of the footing and stem wall. The frictional resistance acting along the base of
footings founded on suitable foundation soils may be computed using a coefficient of friction equal to
0.35 with the normal dead load. Passive earth pressures acting against the side of footings and stem walls
may be assumed to be equivalent to a fluid weighing 300 pounds per cubic foot, provided the ground
surface in front of the footings is level. Passive pressure in the upper 1.0-foot should be neglected unless
confined by concrete slabs-on-grade or asphaltic pavement. The values given above may be increased by
one-third for transient wind or seismic loads.
All footings should maintain a minimum 7-foot horizontal setback from the base of the footing to any
descending slope. This distance is measured from the outside footing face at the bearing elevation.
Footings should maintain a minimum horizontal setback of H/3 (H=slope height) from the base of the
footing to the descending slope face and should be no less than 7 feet, and it need not be greater than
Footings adjacent to unlined drainage swales or underground utilities (if any) should be deepened to a
minimum of 6-inches below the invert of the adjacent unlined swale or utilities. This distance is
measured from the outside footing face at the bearing elevation. Footings for structures adjacent to
retaining walls should be deepened so as to extend below a 1:1 upward projection from the heel of the
wall. Alternatively, walls may be designed to accommodate structural loads from buildings or
appurtenances as described in the retaining wall section of this report.

possible. Design parameters provided herein, therefore, assume that finish grade soil materials will have

Cast-in place concrete guidelines are provided in Lowes Development Criteria, Section 03300 (2008d).
Interior slabs should be supported solely by competent structural fill possessing a very low expansion
potential, whose placement has been observed/tested by the EEI (i.e., the project soils
engineer/engineering geologist). Lowes building design criteria (Section 300; Lowes, 2005) specify that

designed by the structural engineer, per Lowes requirements, or in accordance with the guidelines of the
local governing jurisdiction. For slab-on-grade concrete areas that will be impacted by heavy storage
racks and fork-lift traffic, a modulus of subgrade reaction of 200 psi/in can be used in design. The
concrete slab should be placed over at least 4-inches of free draining, crushed rock or gravel or Caltrans
Class 2 aggregate base material compacted to 98 percent relative compaction (ASTM D-1557) (Lowes,
2006, 2009). To reduce the potential for potential buildup of hydrostatic pressures, the free draining
material under the slabs should have positive drainage with no depressions created. In-place density
testing of the aggregate slab base should be completed no more than 48 hours prior to concrete placement
Floor slabs should be suitably reinforced and jointed (in accordance with the Structural Engineers
recommendations) so that a small amount of independent movement can occur without causing damage.
The contractor should take the appropriate precautions to make sure the reinforcement is placed and
maintained within the middle one-third of the slab.
Exterior slabs, such as walkways and driveways, can be adequately supported on approved structural fill,
which is a minimum of 12-inches in thickness, compacted to at least 95 percent relative compaction
(ASTM D-1557) with at least optimum moisture content.
In preparation for slab or flatwork construction, the earthwork contractor shall ensure that the onsite soils
have been prepared as recommended and that field density tests have been performed to document the
relative compaction of all structural fill. Preparation of the native soils should be documented prior to
placement of aggregate, structural components and/or fill.
Lowes Development Criteria (2006) dictate that Portland Cement Concrete should have a minimum 28-
day compressive strength of at least 4,000 pounds per square inch (psi). Laboratory test results from two
representative samples of the upper soils indicated soluble sulfate concentrations of 47 and 80 milligrams
per kilogram (mg/kg) and chloride concentrations of 31 and 55 mg/kg. As a result, onsite soils appear to
have a negligible corrosion potential to concrete. Based on this information, Type II cement can be used
in concrete that will be in contact with the encountered soils.

adversely affect the finished quality of the concrete and result in cracking and spalling of the slab. We
recommend that all placement and curing be performed in accordance with procedures outlined by the
American Concrete Institute and/or Portland Cement Association. Special consideration should be given
to concrete placed and cured during windy, hot or cold weather conditions. Proper control joints and/or
reinforcing steel should be provided in accordance with the structural engineers requirements to reduce
the potential for damage resulting from shrinkage.

differences between the building interior and exterior ambient conditions, we recommend the use of a
vapor inhibitor in areas of the building where floor coverings are proposed. Consideration should be
given to utilizing at least 10 mil visqueen in these areas. For slabs-on-grade, the visqueen layer should be
placed below the crushed gravel or aggregate base and protected from puncturing by a minimum 2-inch
The geotechnical design parameters provided below are considered preliminary, and assume that non-

For preliminary design purposes, the design active earth pressure on a standard retaining wall may be
considered equivalent to that produced by a fluid weighing 35 pounds per cubic foot (pcf). This design
equivalent fluid pressure of 35 pcf is appropriate for cantilevered walls retaining non-expansive soils
having a level ground surface, subject to lateral deflection at distances above grade due to earth pressure.
A safety factor for sliding and overturning of 1.5 is typically incorporated into the design of a cantilevered
structure as described. All retaining structures should be fully free draining. Restrained walls, with a
level backfill, should be designed for an equivalent fluid pressure of 55 pcf for at rest pressure.
For resistance to lateral loads, an allowable coefficient of friction of 0.35 between the base of the
foundation elements and underlying material is recommended. In addition, an allowable passive
resistance equal to an equivalent fluid weighing 300 pcf acting against the foundation may be used to

page.text: Adequate sub-drainage should be provided behind all retaining walls. The sub-drainage system should
consist of a minimum of a four-inch diameter perforated PVC pipe (schedule 40 or approved equivalent)
placed at the base of the retaining wall and surrounded by 3/4-inch clean crushed rock wrapped in a
Mirafi 140N filter fabric (or approved equivalent). The crushed rock wrapped in fabric should be at least
12-inches wide and extend from the base of the wall to within 2 feet of the ground surface. The upper 2
feet of backfill should consist of compacted native soil. The retaining wall drainage system should be
directed by gravity to an outlet, into the storm drain system or other appropriate facility.
The City of Salinas does not provide retaining wall standard drawings (City of Salinas, 2008); therefore,
retaining wall plans should to be designed by a structural engineer and approved by the City Engineer.

within the upper 18-inches of subgrade (Lowes, 2009). If loose materials are encountered during
